WEBVTT

00:01.300 --> 00:05.293
WILL:
This is no longer a dream.
This is reality.

00:05.330 --> 00:09.437
Three months from now, we are
opening offices in New York.

00:09.470 --> 00:11.301
(applause)
I want to say something.

00:11.340 --> 00:13.228
Not now, Howard.

00:13.280 --> 00:15.373
We are growing.

00:15.410 --> 00:17.105
Share that with your clients.

00:17.150 --> 00:19.539
The era of constriction is over.

00:19.580 --> 00:22.344
Now, a new era

00:22.390 --> 00:24.119
needs new branding.

00:24.790 --> 00:26.087
"LIG."

00:26.120 --> 00:27.553
Own those letters.

00:27.590 --> 00:29.729
No one says
"Lockhart/Gardner" anymore.

00:29.760 --> 00:32.194
It's "L.G."

00:34.330 --> 00:35.729
I'll be right back.

00:35.760 --> 00:37.660
Who's thinking of leaving?

00:37.700 --> 00:39.361
Sonya Rucker. The Wabash Fund.

00:39.400 --> 00:41.288
Chumhum?
No.

00:41.340 --> 00:44.161
Not yet.
Sonya Rucker and Wabash
are leaving Florrick-Agos.

00:44.210 --> 00:45.438
Their infrastructure?
Bad.

00:45.470 --> 00:47.233
Florrick-Agos barely exists.

00:47.280 --> 00:48.508
We've been working out
of Alicia's apartment

00:48.540 --> 00:49.575
for the last two weeks.

00:49.610 --> 00:50.577
That's why I'm
back here.

00:50.610 --> 00:51.838
Did the clients know?
No.

00:51.880 --> 00:54.110
We either met at their offices
or over lunch.

00:54.150 --> 00:55.742
But they are moving
into new offices today.

00:55.780 --> 00:57.213
What offices?
T-shirt factory

00:57.250 --> 00:58.319
on Grand.

00:58.350 --> 01:00.489
Really?
It's all we could...

01:00.520 --> 01:02.226
they could afford.

01:02.260 --> 01:03.488
$20 a square foot.

01:03.530 --> 01:05.589
DIANE:
The connections with the
governor aren't helping AIICIa?

01:05.630 --> 01:07.450
Mm, they're
hurting her.

01:07.500 --> 01:09.661
I lost a client because
of all the ethical issues

01:09.700 --> 01:12.089
from the governor's office.
Thank you,
Anthony.

01:13.140 --> 01:14.391
What a putz.

01:14.440 --> 01:16.431
We should've tried
to get Carey Zepps.

01:16.470 --> 01:17.630
I'll take Rucker.

01:17.670 --> 01:20.434
Will, you take
the Wabash.
(knocking)

01:21.440 --> 01:23.442
I'll be right back.

01:25.150 --> 01:27.448
(chuckles)
How's your course going?

01:27.480 --> 01:30.586
(groans)
When driving in fog,
you should use your...?

01:30.620 --> 01:32.110
Low beams.

01:32.160 --> 01:33.787
That's not true, is it?

01:33.820 --> 01:35.378
It is.

01:35.420 --> 01:37.183
I wrote fog lights.

01:37.230 --> 01:39.425
Why are they called fog lights
if they're not for fog?

01:39.460 --> 01:40.427
To trick you.

01:40.460 --> 01:42.496
(groans)
(chuckles)

01:42.530 --> 01:45.260
How long do you need
my Wi-Fi for?

01:45.300 --> 01:47.268
A few hours.

01:47.300 --> 01:49.268
Want me gone?

01:50.170 --> 01:52.775
Nope. Stay as long as you want.

01:52.810 --> 01:54.300
Mmm.

01:54.340 --> 01:58.447
So, do we have a
Yoko Ono problem here?

01:58.480 --> 02:00.368
Mr. Lee, she's still waiting.

02:00.420 --> 02:02.308
Tell her to come back
tomorrow. Tell her...

02:02.350 --> 02:04.614
all the partners are busy.
I'm not busy.
Who is it?

02:04.650 --> 02:06.481
A walk-in. Not much money.

02:06.520 --> 02:08.158
She says she
used to work here.

02:08.190 --> 02:10.488
I'll take care of it.

02:10.530 --> 02:12.293
So, uh,

02:12.330 --> 02:13.695
you used to work here,
Ms. Flores?

02:13.730 --> 02:15.891
I did. Two years ago.
Ah.

02:15.930 --> 02:17.466
As an intern.

02:17.500 --> 02:18.467
Now you want to come back?

02:18.500 --> 02:19.467
No.

02:19.500 --> 02:21.263
That was a joke.

02:21.300 --> 02:23.734
Breaking the ice.
(chuckles)

02:23.770 --> 02:27.536
So... how can we help you?

02:27.580 --> 02:29.673
A friend of mine has been swept
up in a raid of businesses

02:29.710 --> 02:31.940
employing undocumented workers.
They've threatened

02:31.980 --> 02:33.538
to deport him
back to Mexico

02:33.580 --> 02:35.411
unless he agrees
to a snitch visa...

02:35.450 --> 02:37.589
Oh, so you're from Mexico?

02:37.620 --> 02:39.258
No.
I love Mexico.

02:39.290 --> 02:41.485
I was down there in the '60s.

02:41.520 --> 02:43.351
Puerto Vallarta.

02:43.390 --> 02:44.550
God, the drinks they had.

02:44.590 --> 02:46.455
You know, the ones.
The-the, um...

02:46.500 --> 02:47.819
The ones, um...

02:47.860 --> 02:50.192
What are they called?

02:50.230 --> 02:51.822
I have no idea.

02:51.870 --> 02:52.837
And the women.

02:52.870 --> 02:54.758
In those dresses.
(chuckles)

02:54.800 --> 02:57.462
Those short dresses.

02:57.510 --> 02:58.738
Mmm.

02:58.770 --> 03:01.273
Could you call
Alicia Florrick for me, please?

03:01.310 --> 03:03.642
A-Actually, Alicia doesn't
work here anymore.

03:03.680 --> 03:05.568
She doesn't?

03:05.610 --> 03:06.918
Where is she?

03:06.950 --> 03:09.817
(truck beeping)

03:25.670 --> 03:27.558
CAREY:
Well, here it is.

03:27.600 --> 03:30.967
The furniture should be arriving
in a few hours.

03:31.010 --> 03:32.500
CARY:
Do we have phones, at least?

03:32.540 --> 03:33.768
CAREY:
Not until tomorrow.

03:33.810 --> 03:35.573
We'll have
to work from cells.

03:35.610 --> 03:37.578
CARY:
We can't meet
with Chumhum here.

03:37.610 --> 03:39.316
